{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480143"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:37:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:37:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.36,0.1,0.45,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"18"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54447"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/18"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39956"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"97"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"1201"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11118"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11210"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16576"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44448"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54447"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 45-year-old man presents with a two-day history of intense pain whilst defaecating and associated rectal bleeding. Direct visualisation of the anus shows a superficial laceration that extends just below the dentate line. The area is very tender and digital rectal examination is not possible because of the pain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to basic supportive measures, which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical hydrocortisone","Topical lignocaine","Fissurectomy","Topical glyceryl trinitrate","Botulinum toxin injection into the internal anal sphincter"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an acute anal fissure. The history of anal pain, provoked by defaecation and accompanied by haematochezia is typical. The development of a fissure can often follow an episode of severe constipation. The diagnosis can be confirmed by direct visualisation of the fissure. Any attempted instrumentation (even with the finger) would result in intense pain and spasm of the anal sphincter. Initial treatment is with supportive measures (warm sitz bath, increasing dietary fibre intake, stool softeners) and \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical vasodilators\u003C/strong\u003E (\u003Cstrong\u003Eglyceryl trinitrate\u003C/strong\u003E, diltiazem or nifedipine) for one month. Topical vasodilators work by relaxing the internal anal sphincter and reducing resting anal pressure, thus promoting healing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical hydrocortisone \u003C/strong\u003Eand/or\u003Cstrong\u003E topical lignocaine \u003C/strong\u003Eointments are commonly used to treat haemorrhoids, and while they are commonly used to treat anal fissures, they are less effective than warm sitz baths and oral fibre intake. As such, they would not be the next most appropriate treatment, given conservative management has already been instigated in this patient. Whilst the topical analgesic might relieve the pain, what is needed is a topical vasodilator to help overcome the muscle spasm and facilitate healing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBotulinum toxin injection \u003C/strong\u003Eis considered a second-line therapy, that may be indicated if there is a poor response to topical GTN. Surgical management, such as with a \u003Cstrong\u003Efissurectomy\u003C/strong\u003E, has a higher efficacy rate, but also a higher risk of complications, and is thus reserved for fissures that do not respond to conservative management after ~4-12 weeks. In addition to a fissurectomy, there are other surgical techniques, with lateral internal sphincterotomy as the gold standard surgery for fissures\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most anal fissures can be managed with simple, supportive measures"],"references":["Lohsiriwat V. Anorectal emergencies. World J Surg. 2016; 26:5867-78. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27468181/","Schlichtemeier S, Engel A. Anal fissure. Aust Prescr. 2016;39:14-7. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27041801/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39956"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39956"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-05T00:23:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-05T00:23:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"18"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54447"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\